title: Fighters and mourners of the Ukrainian revolution

aws-transcripts.transcript: When I arrived in Kiev on the first of February this year, Independent Square was under siege, surrounded by police loyal to the government. The protesters who occupied my dan as the squares known, prepared for battle, stockpiling homemade weapons on mass producing improvised body armor. The Euro Maidan protests began peacefully at the end of 2013 after the president of Ukraine, Viktor Yanukovych, rejected a far reaching accord with the European Union in favor of stronger ties with Russia. In response, tens and thousands of dissatisfied citizens poured into central Kiev to demonstrate against this allegiance. As the months passed, confrontations between police and civilians intensified. I set up a makeshift portrait studio by the barricades on her chef's coho st. There I photographed the fighters against a black curtain. A curtain obscured the highly seductive and visual backdrop, a fire, ice and smoke. In order to tell the individual human stories. Here, I felt that I needed to remove the dramatic visuals that had become so familiar and repetitive within the mainstream media. What I was witnessing was not only news but also history. With this realization, I was free from the photo journalistic conventions off the newspaper on the magazine. Oleg, Vassily and Maxim were all ordinary men with ordinary lives from ordinary towns, but the elaborate costumes that they had bedeck themselves in quite extraordinary. I say the word costume because thes were not closed. They had been issued or coordinated by anyone. They were improvised uniforms made up of decommissioned military equipment, irregular combat fatigues and trophies taken from the police. I became interested in the way they were choosing to represent themselves, this outward expression of masculinity, the ideal of the warrior. I worked slowly, using an analog film camera with a manual focusing loop and a handheld light meter. The process is old fashioned. It gives me time to speak with each person and to look at them in silence while they looked back at me. Rising tensions culminated in the worst day of violence on the 20th of February, which became known as Bloody Thursday. Snipers loyal to the government started firing on the civilians and the protesters on Institute School Street. Many were killed in a very short space of time. The reception of the Hotel Ukraina became a makeshift morgue. There were lines of bodies laid in the street, and there was blood all over the pavements. The following day, President Yanukovych fled Ukraine. In all, three months of protests resulted in more than 120 confirmed dead on many more missing. History unfolded quickly, but celebration remained elusive in my Don. As the days passed in Kiev, central square, streams of armed fighters were joined by tens of thousands of ordinary people filling the streets in an act of collective mourning. Many were women who often carried flowers that they had brought to lay as marks of respect for the dead. They came day after day, and they covered the square with millions of flowers. Sadness enveloped my down. It was quiet, and I could hear the birds singing. I hadn't heard that before. I stopped women as they approached the barricades to lay their tributes and asked to make their picture. Most women cried when I photographed them. On the first day, my fixer, Emma and I cried with almost every woman who visited our studio. There had been such a noticeable absence of women up until that point, and the color of their pastel coats. They're shiny handbags on the Bunches of red carnations white tulips and yellow roses that they carried jarred with a black and square on the black and men who were encamped there. It is clear to me that these two sets of pictures don't make much sense without the other. They're about men and women and the way we are, not the way we look, but the way we are. They speak about different gender roles in conflict not only in my Dan and not only in Ukraine. Men fight most wars, and women mourn them if the men showed the ideal of the warrior than the women show the implications of such violence. When I made these pictures, I believe that I was documenting the end of violent events in Ukraine. But now I understand that it is a record of the beginning. Today, the death toll stands around 3000 where hundreds of thousands have been displaced. I was in Ukraine again six weeks ago in my down. The barricades have been dismantled on the paving stones, which were used as weapons during the protests, replaced so that traffic flows freely through the center of the square. The fighters, the women and the flowers are gone, a huge billboard depicting geese flying over a wheat field covers the burnt out shell of the trade unions building on proclaims Glory to Ukraine. Glory to Harris, Thank you.
